      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<p>In 2023, the Malaysian Government proposed a tax incentive for Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) to limit CO2 emissions using CCS technologies while ensuring the achievement of the Low Carbon Nation Aspiration by 2040. <br>The proposed tax incentive scheme includes two mechanisms: </p>\n<p>companies undertaking in-house CCS activity shall receive Investment Tax Allowance of 100% for 10 years, full import duty and sales tax exemption on the equipment used for CCS technology from 2023 to 2027, and tax deduction for pre-commencement expenses within 5 years from the start of operations; <br>companies undertaking CCS services shall receive Investment Tax Allowance of 100% for 10 years, full import duty and sales tax exemption on equipment for CCS technology from 2023 to 2027, and tax exemption of 70% on statuary income for 10 years. In addition, a tax deduction is also given for service fees incurred. </p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/a8c3c46f614f44d5882270d76355f3a6",
      "policyDocumentName": "Malaysian Biofuel Industry Act 2007",
      "sector": "Producers",
      "startDate": "2012",
      "sourceLink": "https://policy.asiapacificenergy.org/node/3981",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Legislative",
      "objectives": "<p>The Malaysia Biofuels Industry Act 2007 introduces a requirement to blend palm oil biodiesel with petroleum diesel (referred to as the B5 blend). Additionally, the act sets up a regulatory framework for licensing activities related to blending, storage, transportation, and the export of palm oil biodiesel. </p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/2a9b68cd8b5342cab7dd4aeb7a620220",
      "policyDocumentName": "Electric Vehicle Taskforce",
      "sector": "EV market boost",
      "startDate": "2022",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.mida.gov.my/malaysias-shift-towards-green-mobility/ ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<p>\"To address the issues and challenges, the Government has formed an Electric Vehicle Taskforce to facilitate policy formation on EV and to streamline EV incentives towards the adoption of EV in Malaysia. This initiative is in line with the National Investment Aspirations (NIA) to elevate the focus on Environmental, Social and Corporate Governance (ESG) issues across all sectors.  </p>\n<p>The established Taskforce is currently looking into rationalising the EV agenda in Malaysia, and proposing recommendations for a comprehensive policy, which will help encourage EV manufacturers to make Malaysia their automated regional hub and to propel the adoption of EV as the preferred choice of local consumers. As the co-secretariat alongside MITI, MIDA is actively committed to attracting potential investment to Malaysia, while seizing opportunities to spur the EV automotive segment.\"</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/024af4db0ec94a90b9b9d6561c22056d",
      "policyDocumentName": "Tax Incentive for Manufacturer of Electric Vehicle Charging Equipment",
      "sector": "EV market boost",
      "startDate": "2023",
      "endDate": "2025",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.iea.org/policies/17249-tax-incentive-for-manufacturer-of-electric-vehicle-charging-equipment ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<h4>Second source:</h4>\n<p><a href=\"https://budget.mof.gov.my/pdf/belanjawan2023/ucapan/tax-measure.pdf\">https://budget.mof.gov.my/pdf/belanjawan2023/ucapan/tax-measure.pdf</a></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>To promote electric mobility, in 2023 the Malaysian government introduced a tax incentive to attract investment in the manufacturing of electric vehicle charging equipment, ensuring local production at a competitive cost. </p>\n<p>The proposed tax exemption includes: <br>100% income tax exemption for a 10 years period, from 2023 to 2032, for manufacturing companies that make early investments in 2023. Companies investing after 2023 will receive the remaining exemption period only; <br>100% Investment Tax Allowance for a 5 years period for manufacturing companies that can be compensated by up to 100% of their statutory income for each year.</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/2b6804f27fb44228964f5a92a57a04c3",
      "policyDocumentName": "Tax Incentive for Company Renting Non-Commercial Electric Vehicle",
      "sector": "EV market boost",
      "startDate": "2023",
      "endDate": "2025",
      "sourceLink": "https://budget.mof.gov.my/pdf/belanjawan2023/ucapan/tax-measure.pdf",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<p>To promote the use of low-carbon vehicles, in 2023 the Malaysian Government introduced new tax incentives for companies renting non-commercial motor vehicles, including Electric Vehicles (EV). </p>\n<p>Currently, a tax deduction is given to companies under Section 39 (1)(k) of the Income Tax Act 1967 based on the following conditions: </p>\n<p><br>If the cost of the vehicle does not exceed RM150,000, companies will receive a tax deduction on the rental amount up to RM100,000;<br>If the cost of the vehicle exceeds RM150,000, companies will receive a tax deduction on the rental amount up to RM50,000.</p>\n<p><br>In 2023, the Government proposed to increase the tax deduction to companies renting non-commercial motor vehicles including EVs up to RM300,000. This measure will be effective from 2023 until 2025.</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/cad3251940c84f9fa03a4f16278db89d",
      "policyDocumentName": "Battery Electric Vehicle Global Leaders Initiative (BEV GLI)",
      "sector": "EV market boost",
      "startDate": "2023",
      "endDate": "2025",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.trade.gov/market-intelligence/malaysia-electric-vehicles https://www.mida.gov.my/malaysias-shift-towards-green-mobility/ ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<p>The BEV program allows foreign companies to sell cars in Malaysia without Approved Permit (AP) rules, thus making imported vehicles cheaper. This initiative aims to help boost EV demand in the local market and further promote the development of the ecosystem to support BEV adoption. </p>\n<p>Incentives include offering exemptions for whole import duty, excise duty, and sales tax for locally-assembled EV until 31 December 2025, and exemptions for whole import duty and excise duty for imported EV until 31 December 2023 – will simultaneously support EV manufacturers and encourage EV ownership, which is expected to raise the EV industry and ecosystem while also allowing for more green investments and for the creation of high-skilled job opportunities in Malaysia.</p>\n<p>Additionally, there will be tax exemptions that will come into play. A road tax exemption of up to 100% will be provided for EV on top of individual income tax relief of up to RM2,500 for the purchase, installation, rent, hire purchase, and subscription fees for EV charging facilities. Special tax incentives are also available for the development of critical EV components (as mentioned earlier).</p>\n<p>All of these policies and initiatives are being set down for the next couple of years, as the Government targets for Malaysia to participate signiﬁcantly in the regional electric mobility market by 2030. </p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/a43e313347a146d4804e780785889297",
      "policyDocumentName": "Low Carbon Transition Facility (LCTF)",
      "sector": "Small and Medium Enterprises (SME)",
      "startDate": "2022",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.bnm.gov.my/lctf2022_en_broc ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<p>In 2022, Bank Negara Malaysia (BNM), the Central Bank of Malaysia, launched a new Low Carbon Transition Facility (LCTF) under BNM’s fund for Small Medium Enterprises (SME). LCTF is a financing facility to encourage the commitment of SMEs in all sectors towards low carbon and sustainable business operations through financing capital expenditure. </p>\n<p>The Low Carbon Transition Facility is open for SMEs in all sectors that are committed<br>to transform their business operations towards low carbon operations. This includes<br>improving energy efficiency, increasing use of sustainable material for production and<br>obtaining sustainability certification.</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/e1e485e7a8b8456b94e29aa6709df413",
      "policyDocumentName": "Green Technology Financing Scheme",
      "sector": "All sectors",
      "startDate": "2010",
      "endDate": "2025",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.gtfs.my/ ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<p>GTFS 1.0 offered a rebate of 2% per annum on interest or profit rates charged by financial institutions, while also providing a Government guarantee of 60% for the green cost of the financed amount. In addition to providing the GTFS 1.0 finacing facilities, GTFS 2.0 provides financing through green bond (“sukuk”) issuances. An amount of up to RM2.0 billion sukuk issuance is available, with the maximum of RM300 million for each company and a maximum period of 15 years for energy producer companies and 10 years for energy user companies. Apart from the category of producer and user companies benefiting under this scheme, GTFS 2.0 also supports Energy Services Company (ESCOs), where RM1.0 billion has been exclusively allocated to finance investments or assets related to energy-efficient projects and Energy Performance Contract. An ESCO is eligible to secure financing of up to RM25 million for a period of up to 5 years.<br>The bulk of projects approved are in the renewable energy sector which accounted to more than 80% of the loans approved. The approved projects are anticipated to contribute to the avoidance of over 3.7 million tonnes of CO2 equivalent every year. The GTFS has been instrumental in encouraging the participation of private financial institutions to invest in green ventures and it has brought together a total of 29 banks and financial institutions to participate in the Scheme. With increasing numbers of entrepreneurs venturing into the green technology sector, GTFS will continue to be an important enabler bridging financing gaps and empowering emerging green businesses in the country.</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/9692dbf8619349828c03c7524d6a107a",
      "policyDocumentName": "Electricity Regulations (Amendment) 2013 ",
      "sector": "Household sector",
      "startDate": "2013",
      "sourceLink": "\"https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1757-899X/341/1/012022#:~:text=One%20of%20Malaysia's%20key%20strategies,Electricity%20Regulations%20(Amendment)%202013",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Legislative",
      "objectives": "<h4>Second source:</h4>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.st.gov.my/en/web/application/details/2/20\">https://www.st.gov.my/en/web/application/details/2/20</a></p>\n<p>One of Malaysia's key strategies to promote efficient energy use in the country is to implement the minimum energy performance standards (MEPS) through the Electricity Regulations (Amendment) 2013. Five selected electrical appliances (refrigerator, air conditioner, television, domestic fans and lamp fittings) must comply with MEPS requirement in order to be sold in Malaysian market. Manufacturers, importers or distributors are issued Certificate of Approval (COA) if products are MEPS-compliant.<br><br></p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/56ddb9a93b404578a608a9e95da633a6",
      "policyDocumentName": "Energy efficiency and use of renewable energy for non-residential buildings - Code of practice",
      "sector": "Residential Buildings",
      "startDate": "2017",
      "sourceLink": "https://policy.asiapacificenergy.org/node/1268 ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Legislative",
      "objectives": "<p> This code of practice gives guidance on the design, selection of materials and electrical appliances and efficient use of energy including the application of renewable energy in new and existing residential buildings.</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/b61ae3de4f6c4e5bb3d75a0c1c831fae",
      "policyDocumentName": "Efficient Management of Electrical Energy Regulations 2008 ",
      "sector": "Large energy consumers",
      "startDate": "2008",
      "sourceLink": "https://policy.asiapacificenergy.org/node/1207#:~:text=(1)%20These%20Regulations%20shall%20apply,months%3B%20or%20(b)%20any ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Legislative",
      "policyInstruments": "",
      "objectives": "<h4>Second source</h4>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.iea.org/policies/2387-efficient-management-of-electrical-energy-regulations-2008\">https://www.iea.org/policies/2387-efficient-management-of-electrical-energy-regulations-2008</a></p>\n<p>The Electricity Energy Regulations were issued in 2008 as provided by the Electricity Supply Act 1990. After a preliminary part, they deal with \"\"Electrical Energy Management\"\", \"\"Registered Electrical Energy Management\"\" and with a general part. he law covers two main items:<br>1. requirement to disclose energy consumption for large electric energy consumers (3 000 000 kWhr or greater within 6 consecutive months). Failure to do so entails a fine not exceeding 5000 MYR<br>2. requirement that a registered electrical energy manager conducts the audit.</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/ab615d6dcd1c47209138ad0ffd3612e6",
      "policyDocumentName": "Renewable Energy Act 2011",
      "sector": "Renewable Energy Act 2011\tRenewable Energy",
      "startDate": "2011",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.seda.gov.my/policies/renewable-energy-act-2011/ ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Legislative",
      "objectives": "<p>The Renewable Energy Act was enforced in 2011 to accelerate contribution from green energy such as solar photovoltaic (PV), biomass, biogas and mini hydro in Malaysia’s electricity generation mix. The Act provides for the establishment and implementation of FiT special tariff system to catalyse the generation of renewable energy.<br><br></p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/15293e607c6542d5855927cd63952094",
      "policyDocumentName": "Sustainable Energy Development Authority Act 2011",
      "sector": "Energy Sector",
      "startDate": "2011",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.seda.gov.my/policies/sustainable-energy-development-authority-act-2011/ ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Legislative",
      "objectives": "<p>The Sustainable Energy Development Authority (SEDA) was established through the Sustainable Energy Development Authority Act of 2011, with its primary responsibility being the supervision and management of the renewable energy feed-in tariff program as outlined in the Renewable Energy Act of 2011.</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/6fce62d8a7c14dd59f290e86299895fe",
      "policyDocumentName": "Net Energy Metering Scheme",
      "sector": "Energy Sector",
      "startDate": "2016",
      "endDate": "2023",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.seda.gov.my/reportal/nem/ ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Legislative",
      "objectives": "<p>The government of Malaysia introduced the Net Energy Metering Scheme in November 2016 with quota allocation of 500 MW up to year 2020 to encourage Malaysia’s Renewable Energy (RE) uptake. The concept of NEM is that the energy produced from the solar PV installation will be consumed first, and any excess will be exported to TNB at prevailing displaced cost.</p>\n<p>As an effort to encourage the NEM uptake, the NEM 2.0 was introduced on 1st January 2019, and the true net energy metering concept was adopted, where it allows excess solar PV generated energy to be exported back to the grid on a “one-on-one” offset basis.  The 500MW quota under the NEM 2.0 has been fully subscribed by 31st December 2020.<br>Due to overwhelming response from the PV industry and in an effort to boost the usage of Solar energy, the Energy and Natural Resources Minister via a press statement by KeTSA on 29th December 2020 has introduced the new Net Energy Metering 3.0 programme (NEM 3.0) to provide more opportunities to electricity consumers to install solar PV systems on the roofs of their premises to save on their electricity bill. The NEM 3.0 will be in effect from 2021 to 2023 and the total quota allocation is up to 1050 MW. </p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/e54d6523be9247e49aac8a0aaa37f8eb",
      "policyDocumentName": "Large Scale Solar Program",
      "sector": "Industry",
      "startDate": "2016",
      "sourceLink": "\"https://hsfnotes.com/malaysia/2021/06/30/a-glimpse-into-the-renewable-energy-initiatives-in-malaysia-one-step-closer-to-a-greener-future/  ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<h4>Second source</h4>\n<p>https://www.seda.gov.my/about-seda/re-programmes/</p>\n<p>Large Scale Solar or known as LSS is a competitive bidding programme to drive down the Levelized Cost of Energy  (LCOE) for the development of large scale solar photovoltaic plant (LSS) and Energy Commission is the implementing agency for this scheme.</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/b4c33e50d3bd4990b8c9d763febe1f16",
      "policyDocumentName": "Green Building Index (GBI)",
      "sector": "Buildings (residential, commercial)",
      "startDate": "2009",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.greenbuildingindex.org/",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<p>The Green Building Index (GBI) is Malaysia’s industry recognised green rating tool for buildings to promote sustainability in the built environment and raise awareness among Developers, Architects, Engineers, Planners, Designers, Contractors and the Public about environmental issues and government's responsibility to the future generations.</p>\n<p>The GBI rating tool provides an opportunity for developers and building owners to design and construct green, sustainable buildings that can provide energy savings, water savings, a healthier indoor environment, better connectivity to public transport and the adoption of recycling and greenery for their projects and reduce our impact on the environment. GBI is a voluntary and not a statutory requirement and GBI Accredition Panel is responsible for issuing all GBI certification</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Malaysia"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/b337e5531bcb4e67b1e9b92b0c02a583",
      "policyDocumentName": "Carbon Pricing Act",
      "sector": "Industry",
      "startDate": "2019",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.nea.gov.sg/our-services/climate-change-energy-efficiency/climate-change/carbon-tax ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Legislative",
      "objectives": "<h4>Second source</h4>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.mse.gov.sg/policies/climate-change/cpa\">https://www.mse.gov.sg/policies/climate-change/cpa</a></p>\n<p>To incentivise emissions reductions across all sectors and support the transition to a low-carbon economy. There are no exemptions for covered facilities, to maintain a transparent, fair, and consistent price signal across the economy. The carbon tax mechanism is also supported by a robust measurement, reporting and verification (MRV) framework.<br>The carbon tax level was set at S$5/tCO2e for the first five years from 2019 to 2023 to provide a transitional period for emitters to adjust. The carbon tax will be raised to S$25/tCO2e in 2024 and 2025, and S$45/tCO2e in 2026 and 2027, with a view to reaching S$50-80/tCO2e by 2030. </p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Singapore"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/565d39a33b204c579bff880155261a07",
      "policyDocumentName": "Resource Efficiency Grant for Energy (RE G(E))",
      "sector": "Industry",
      "startDate": "2018",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.edb.gov.sg/en/how-we-help/incentives-and-schemes.html ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<p>The Resource Efficiency Grant for Emissions (REG(E)) aims to encourage improvement in energy efficiency of manufacturing facilities and data centres. The REG(E) is part of the Enhanced Industry Energy Efficiency package, with the Energy Market Authority (EMA), Singapore Economic Development Board (EDB) and the National Environment Agency (NEA) each rolling out initiatives to extend stronger support to companies in their drive to become more energy efficient and reduce carbon emissions.</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Singapore"
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f10d08d3-d4e4-4111-adeb-82ecc0e7d452",
      "udi": "umb://element/9b359bf839f1449db6ee6e2575d564e2",
      "policyDocumentName": "Investment Allowance (Energy Efficiency) (“IA-EE”) scheme",
      "sector": "Industry",
      "startDate": "2021",
      "endDate": "2026",
      "sourceLink": "https://www.iras.gov.sg/news-events/singapore-budget/budget-2021---overview-of-tax-changes ",
      "policyLevel": "National",
      "policyOrigin": "Bureaucratic",
      "objectives": "<h4>Second source</h4>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.nccs.gov.sg/singapores-climate-action/mitigation-efforts/industry/\">https://www.nccs.gov.sg/singapores-climate-action/mitigation-efforts/industry/</a></p>\n<p>The IA-EE scheme will ain for-<br>a) Expansion in the scope of qualifying projects involving a reduction of greenhouse gas emissions; and<br>b) Streamlined and updated eligibility conditions, to include data centres and non-data centres</p>\n<p>The investment allowance is granted on capital expenditure incurred for energy-efficient or green data centre projects. Companies that adopt energy-efficient technologies to build capabilities and decarbonise early can receive up to 70 per cent of qualifying costs.</p>",
      "policyInventoryCountry": [
        "Singapore"
      ]
    },
    {
